                    <h2>The Legend of Coffee</h2>
                    <p>There is no real evidence about the discovery of coffee, but there are many legends that report its possible origin.</p>
                    <p>One of the most accepted and disseminated is that of Pastor Kaldi, who lived in Absinia, now Ethiopia, about a thousand years ago. It says that Kaldi noticed that his goats were cheerful and bouncy, and this extra energy was evident whenever they chewed the reddish-yellow fruits of the bushes in some grazing fields.</p>
                    <p>The shepherd noticed that the fruits were a source of joy and motivation, and only with their help could the flock walk for several kilometers by endless climbs.</p>
                    <p>Kaldi commented on the behavior of the animals to a monk in the region, who decided to experience the power of the fruits. The monk took some of the fruit and took it with him to the monastery. He began to use the fruits in the form of infusion, realizing that the drink helped him resist sleep while praying or in his long hours of reading the breviary. This discovery spread rapidly among the monasteries, creating a demand for the drink. Evidence shows that the coffee was first grown in Islamic monasteries in Yemen.</p>
