                    <h2>The First Coffee Crops</h2>
                    <p>Coffee plant is originally from Ethiopia, central Africa, where it is still part of the natural vegetation. Arabia was responsible for the spread of coffee culture. The name coffee does not originate from Kaffa, the plant's place of origin, but from the Arabic word “Qahwa”.</p>
                    <p>The oldest manuscripts mentioning the coffee culture date from 575 in Yemen, where, consumed as fresh fruit, it is now cultivated. Only in the sixteenth century, in Persia, the first coffee beans were roasted to become the drink we know today.</p>
                    <p>Coffee became of great importance to the Arabs, who had complete control over the cultivation and preparation of the drink. At that time, coffee was a product kept under the Arabs. It was forbidden for foreigners to approach plantations, and Arabs protected the seedlings with their own lives. The coffee seed off the parchment does not sprout, so only in these conditions could the seeds leave the country.</p>
                    <p>From 1615 the café began to be enjoyed in the European Continent, brought by travelers on their frequent trips to the east. Until the 17th century, only Arabs produced coffee. Germans, French and Italians desperately sought a way to develop planting in their colonies. But it was the Dutch who got the first seedlings and cultivated them in the greenhouses of the Botanical Garden of Amsterdam, a fact that made the drink one of the most consumed in the old continent, becoming a definitive part of the habits of Europeans.</p>
                    <p>From these plants, the Dutch started in 1699, experimental plantations in Java. This successful experience has brought profit, encouraging other countries to try the same. Europe marveled at coffee as a decorative plant, while the Dutch expanded the cultivation to Sumatra, and the French, presented with a coffee foot by the burgomaster of Amsterdam, began testing on the islands of Sandwich and Bourbon.</p>
                    <p>With the Dutch and French experiments, coffee cultivation was taken to other European colonies. The growing European consumer market has led to the expansion of coffee plantations in African countries and their arrival in the New World. At the hands of European settlers, coffee arrived in Suriname, São Domingos, Cuba, Puerto Rico and Guyana. It was through the Guianas that he arrived in northern Brazil. In this way, the secret of the Arabs spread to every corner of the world.</p>
