                    <h2>Coffee in Brazil</h2>
                    <p>Reed approached the wife of the governor of Cayenne, capital of French Guiana, managing to win his trust. Thus, a small seedling of Arabica coffee was offered clandestinely and brought hidden in the luggage of this Brazilian.</p>
                    <p>Under favorable conditions the culture was initially established in the Paraíba River Valley, starting in 1825 a new economic cycle in the country. At the end of the 18th century, Haiti's coffee production -- until then the world's leading exporter of the product -- went into crisis due to the country's long war of independence against France. Taking advantage of this situation, Brazil significantly increased its production and, although still on a small scale, began to export the product more regularly. The shipments were made for the first time in 1779, with the insignificant amount of 79 arrobas. In 1806 alone, exports reached a more significant volume of 80,000 arrobas.</p>
