                <div>
                    <p>For almost a century, coffee was the great Brazilian wealth, and the currencies generated by the coffee economy accelerated the development of Brazil and inserted it in international trade relations. The coffee culture occupied valleys and mountains, enabling the emergence of cities and the urbanization of important urban centers throughout the interior of the State of São Paulo, south of Minas Gerais and northern Paraná. Railroads were built to allow the flow of production, replacing animal transport and boosting interregional trade in other important goods. Coffee brought large contingents of immigrants, consolidated the expansion of the middle class, diversification of investments and even intensified cultural movements. From then on, coffee and the Brazilian people are inseparable.</p>
                    <p>The wealth flowed through the Cafezais, evidenced in the elegant mansions of the farmers, who brought European culture to the theaters erected in the new cities of the interior of São Paulo. For ten decades Brazil has grown, driven by the habit of coffee, served in half-world meals, internalizing our culture, building factories, promoting racial miscegenation, dominating political parties, overthrowing the monarchy and abolishing slavery.</p>
                    <p>Besides being the source of many of Brazilian riches, coffee allowed some extraordinary feats. For a long time, the best-known Brazilian coffee in the world was the Santos type. The quality of Santista coffee and the fact that it is one of the main exporting ports of the product, determined the creation of Café Tipo Santos.</p>
                    <p>Implanted with minimal knowledge of the culture, in regions that later became inadequate for its cultivation, coffee growing in south-central Brazil began to have problems in 1870, when a great frost hit the plantations of western São Paulo causing incalculable damage.</p>
                    <p>After a long crisis, the national coffee industry reorganized and producers, industrialists and exporters returned to feed hopes for a better future. The search for the ideal region for coffee culture has spread throughout the country, establishing itself today in regions of the State of São Paulo, Minas Gerais, Paraná, Espírito Santo, Bahia and Rondônia. Coffee continues today, to be one of the most important products for Brazil and is undoubtedly the most Brazilian of all. Today the country is the first producer and the second world consumer of the product.</p>
