                <div>
                    <h2>The path of Coffee Cultivation in Brazil</h2>
                    <p>The first planting occurred in 1727, in Pará. Due to its climatic conditions, coffee cultivation spread rapidly.</p>
                    <p>The starting point of the great plantations was Rio de Janeiro, with the Tijuca forests becoming large coffee plantations. The coffee extends to Angra dos Reis, Parati and arrived in São Paulo by Ubatuba. In a short time, the Paraíba River valley became the great region producing coffee plantations in Brazil. This region with excellent altitude and climate for cultivation, allowed the emergence of a centralizing area of crops and population. Rising up the river, the café invaded the eastern part of the province of São Paulo and the border region of Minas Gerais. At the time, Rio de Janeiro was the port of product outflow and financial center.</p>
                    <p>However, coffee culture in areas with a steep slope and total carelessness regarding soil preservation generated an intense erosion. For this reason, the land was quickly exhausted and the coffee culture migrated to another location, the west of the province of São Paulo, centralizing in Campinas and extending to Ribeirão Preto.</p>
                    <p>Campinas became the great producer pole of the country. The crops stretched out on large uniform surfaces, covering the landscape to lose sight of, forming the famous "coffee seas". In the region, the Cafezais suffered less from soil depletion by the flat surface of the region, which also facilitated communication and transport and provided a concentration of wealth. While a complex system of railway roads was established in the Paraíba Valley, a good network of road and rail roads was established in this new region. With this new producer pole, the coffee changed its distribution center, being all the production of the west of São Paulo and then exported from the port of Santos.</p>
