                <div>
                    <p>The development of coffee production was closely related to the amount of manpower available. To encourage coffee production, the administration of the State of São Paulo made the immigration issue the central project of its activities, establishing a system that offered formal assistance to European immigration, especially the Italian one. Through a program that handled advertising in their country of origin, immigrants were brought from their homes in Europe to the coffee farm. Immigration has helped to conquer areas not yet explored, allowing rapid development of the State of São Paulo.</p>
                    <p>With the immigrant workforce the culture gained momentum and for three quarters of a century, almost all of the country's wealth has focused on coffee farming. Brazil dominated 70% of the world's production and dictated the rules of the market. At that time coffee farmers became the social and political elite, forming one of the last Brazilian aristocracies. The opulence of coffee planters allowed the construction of large and beautiful mansions of farms and mansions in the city of São Paulo and financed industrialization in the southeast of the country.</p>
                </div>
                <div>
                    <h2>Brazilian Coffee Today</h2>
                    <p>Currently Brazil is the world's largest producer of coffee, accounting for 30% of the international market, a volume equivalent to the sum of production of the other six largest producing countries. It is also the second consumer market, behind only the United States.</p>
                    <p>The coffee areas are concentrated in the south-central part of the country, where four producing states stand out: Minas Gerais, São Paulo, Espírito Santo and Paraná. The Northeast region also has plantations in Bahia, and from the North region there is Rondônia.</p>
                    <p>Arabica coffee production is concentrated in São Paulo, Minas Gerais, Paraná, Bahia and part of Espírito Santo, while Robusta coffee is planted mainly in Espírito Santo and Rondônia.</p>
